04565nam a22005535i 9780774851862DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072004xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748518627 a10.59962/97807748518622doi  a(DE-B1597)661068  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aZ462.86.S46.R44 2004eb 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a686.2091 aReed, Christopher A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGutenberg in Shanghai :bChinese Print Capitalism, 1876-1937 /cChristopher A. Reed. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (408 p.) :b45 b&w illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary Chinese Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tGutenberg’s Descendants: Transferring Industrialized Printing Technology to China, 1807–1930 -- tJanus-Faced Pioneers: The Golden Age of Shanghai’s Lithographic Printer-Publishers, 1876–1905 -- t“Sooty Sons of Vulcan”: Forging Shanghai’s Printing Machinery, 1895–1937 -- t“The Hub of the Wheel”: Commerce, Technology, and Organizational Innovation in Shanghai’s New-Style Publishing World, 1876–c. 1911 -- t“The Three Legs of the Tripod”: Commercial Press, Zhonghua Books, and World Books, 1912–37 -- tConclusion -- tA Bird’s-Eye View of 1930s Shanghai’s Fuzhou Road/Wenhuajie District -- tGlossary of Chinese Terms, Titles, and Names -- tNotes -- tSelected Asian-Language Bibliography -- tSelected Western-Language Bibliography -- tIndex -- tStudies of the Weatherhead East Asian Institute0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the mid-1910s, what historians call the "Golden Age of Chinese Capitalism" began, accompanied by a technological transformation that included the drastic expansion of China's "Gutenberg revolution." Gutenberg in Shanghai examines this process. It finds the origins of that revolution in the country's printing industries of the late imperial period and analyzes their subsequent development in the Republican era. This book, which relies on documents previously unavailable to both Western and Chinese researchers, demonstrates how Western technology and evolving traditional values resulted in the birth of a unique form of print capitalism whose influence on Chinese culture was far-reaching and irreversible. Its conclusion contests scholarly arguments that view China's technological development as slowed by culture, or that interpret Chinese modernity as mere cultural continuity. A vital reevaluation of Chinese modernity, Gutenberg in Shanghai will be enthusiastically received by scholars of Chinese history and by specialists in cultural studies, political science, sociology, the history of the book, and the anthropology of science and technology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPrintingzChinazShanghaixHistory. 0aPublishers and publishingzChinazShanghaixHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485186240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774851862423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774851862/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles